o went down to defeat in Novem\nber, and it will be necessary for some\none else to do for the senate tho think\ning which ho did for it in the past\nThree other members of the last twe\nsenates, all republicans who might\nhave \"come back\u201d had it been their de\nsire la do so. are among those whe\nwill not ba present next Tuesday.\nThey ar\u00ab Charles W. Riner and Ar\nchle Allison of Laramie county ano\nH. D. Sdmonda, tht handsome member\nfrom Park county.\nWOMEN KEPTIN\nPRE-WAR JOBS\nONLY FEW DISCHABOED WHEN\n\u2022OLDtEftS BCtOAN fWOM FRONT\nIN SOME LARGE .CITIES.\nBy Iba Aasaelaud Pram\nChicago. Jan. B.\u2014Only part of the\nwomen engaged In Industry during\nwar period have lost their placet\nthrough the return of men from the\nwar and the lack of employment. Mist\nMary Anderson, director Of the worn\nen\u2019e tbnreau of the' United states ?De\npartment of Labor, reports.\n\"Statements to the bureau from hun\ndreds of industry, heads who empioyeu\nonly women during the war show they\nhave retained their female help, while\nothers.state they have replaced theli\nwomen with male workers,\u201d MUe An\nderaon said.\n\"Because of the volume of unem\nployment throughout the country to\n;day no accurate figures as to the\nnumber of women employed in indus\ntries at present as compared with tbh\nwar period are obtainable.\nMilllone at Work\n\u201cI. believe. that when figures of the\n1920 census are avaffcble, they wU.\nshow more than 12,000,000 Women ir.\ngainful Occupation. The* census, how\never, will nqt set forth the preaeut\nsituation because unemployment has\ntnerdased by Veeps and bounds sipct\nit was taken.\n\u201cWomen won the admiration of om\nployers durlng the war period hy theb\nability to till in on men's jobs. Takr\nfor instance lathe operators. ThouS\nsods of women became- ve<y efficient\nand still retain their places beside\nmen operators. The war gave Amer\nlean women a new opportunity in in\ndustry and they grasped it.\u201d\nThere are two factors needed to In\nsure women their place in industry\nMiss Anderson said. Protective legis\nlatlon for the eight-hour day is badl;\nneeded, she declared, and added that\nthe women must \"organize within th\nnlext tew years.\u201d\nWith the return of prosperity, In\ndnstries will -clamor for women work\ners. In the opinion of Afis* Mary E\nMcDowell of the University of Ch!\ncago Settlement house, who Is chah\nman of tho women In industry com\nmitten of the National League o\nWomen Voters.\nDEED FILED BY CITY\nFOR BLOCK FOR PARk\ni The deed from C* L* Patchell an;\nwife to the city of Laramie, transfer\nj ing block 14, University Place add!\n1 tion Cur park and playground -purposes\nwhich-tho city occupied with heart.\u2019\nthanks on Tuesday night, has beet\nfiled lor record. Mr. and Mrs. Patch\nell donated the block to be used bj\nthe city for park purposes and stipu\nla ted that no other buildings shouk\nbe erected nearer than fifteen fee\nof the outer lines of the block. War\nranty deeds from W. T. Donnell, trus\ntee, to W. A. Crawford, for lots 4, b\n6 and 7. block 2. Peirce addition t<\nRock River, for >l, and\u2019from Alfre<\nNelson and wife to Ole Berglund ant\nWife, for the west forty-two feot o\nlots 1, 2 and 3 block 278, Sherod's ad\nditlon td Laramie, also' for (1, wen\nfiled ter record.\n\u25a0MN new'studbnts\nAFTER THE HOLIQAYI\nTen nevr studenta have enrolled a\nthe University ot Wyomikt sines th\nholidays, all but one of them men.\nebanlemcilnc any lorn to numhen\ntoom students who did ndt return Al\nter voaauoa. Work is well started\nAnd everything is Coing smothly it\ntke ctoM.rooms.\nmarried By MINISTER\n.OFMCTHODiCT CHURCI\nJoaOM Berten Frederick end Mrs\u2019\nBessie TatMm Rogers, to whom s\nmaniocs Uconoe was issoed a lev\ndaystOEO, wore married by Rev. Lawl,\nft.CMWV, Mator .ts the MMhodlr\nohureh.\nViCFTINB AT MKVI*\nFOR A FEW DAYE\nMr. and Mm. Elmer Bowman left\non the Denver train tor that city thl.\n\u25a0horning, intending to visit for a .tea\ndays la the Colorado metropolis.\nr LAftAMS\nSME LIFE\nIN THE AIR\nMEDICAL ADVICE GY RADIO BEING\nUSED TO HELP UNTIL AT-\nTENTION CAN BE GIVEN\nBy the Aaeociated I'reea.\nNew York, Jun. 7. \u2014Medical advlct\nby radio, designed to have life in event\nof slcknosa or accident at sea by ap\nplying proper treatment until personal\nservice of a physician or surgeon can\nbe obtained is now possible.\nA new emergency radio call \u2014the\nletters \"KDKF\u201d has been established,\nplanned to take its plate with the in\nternational S. O. S. call of vessels hr\ndistress.\nThis call Is intended to take prece\ndence in the ever increasing radio ser\nvice over all other business except the\ndistress signal\u2014for it means that in\ndividual life is in danger and nssis\ntance is being asked for.\nA recent arrangement between th.\nSeaman's church Institute of New\nYork and the navy department estab\nlished here a school of medical In\nitruction for olUcers and seamen.\nMariners trained in this school i!\ncalled upon to treat a serious illness\nor accident case at sea can communi\ncate by radio to tho physician at the\nSeamans\u2019 institute and receive from\nhim Instructions to be followed until\nthe ship reached a harbor or obtaim>\nassistance from another vessel.\nThe medical officer in New York b\n'on watch\u201d from 2 to 10 p. m.\u00bb for thb\nservice.\nIS CHAMPION WOMAN\nRIDER OF THE WORLD\nWBm\nMias Lorena Trlckey won the title of\nall-around champion woman rider of\ntho world at the recent \u201cFrontier days\u201d\nround-up at Cheyenne, Wyo. Her title\nIncludes nnchatlenged auprenmey In\nbtenco-bustlng, relay riding, Roman\nstanding racing, trick riding, as well\nas more ordinary equestrian events.\nMiss Trlckey Is a typical western range\ngirl, raised on the ranch whore she\nlearned her remarkable horsewoman\nship.\nBAILS SELF OUT OF JAIL\nBut Atlanta Man Finds It Good Ref\nuge on Cold Night, and Returns.\nW. T. Boswell, forty-eight, evidently\nbelieves the Atlanta police statiou Is\na good refuge on a cold night, even\nwith Its ordinary inconveniences.\nWhen found Intoxicated In the\nstreets. Boswell was locked In a cell,\nwith furnace heat and blanketed cot.\nAt the end of two hours he put up $6\ncollateral and asked Io be released.\nIt may have been the cold wind that\nname whistling around the corner of\nthe police station or It may have been\nthe long tiresome trip home that dis\ncouraged him. At any rate, he turned\nback.\n\u201cI ain't right yet, gentlemen.\u201d he\nsaid, as be displayed all the symp\ntoms of a drunk on the police station\n.steps. \u201cMy head's thlclk as crab grass\nunder the edge of the term porch. Give\nme back my .$6 and let me stay two\nmore houra.\u201d\nBit money was refunded and he\nwas given a bed ter the night.\nWOMEN fIJffHEIKDBRICKS\nLittle Band es Weekem.Cleaned Build.\nIng Material for Church.\nForty thousand used bricks and a\nliantlty of sand have been gathered to\nigeiher by a small group of women In\nliTovey. nt, for the constnteHbn of\nchurch. The women cleaned the\nbricks themselves, devoting a part of\n>(\u00bbech morning until the work was com-\nTiered. They obtained the wind from\nhe railroad tracks, where It had bean\numped from box cars,\nRANCHMAN HERE\nAND SPENT THE NIGHT\nMr. and Mrs. D. O. Herrick drove\na from the ranch yesterday afternoon\nand spent the nibt here, returning to\nthe country today.\nWONDERING ABOUT\nWHERE BLAME CAME\nTwo young women who narrowly\nescaped being run down on the pave\nment in front of one of the garages,\nby an automobile coming from the\ndoor of the garage, are wondering\njust where thp blame would lie had\nthey been struck. They aver that the\nautomobile came out without any.\nwarning whatever, and ran across the\nsidewalk. One of the girla was able\nto jump forward Just in time to be\nmissed and the other backed away\nfrom danger. Autos coming from gar\nages and from the filling stations ai\nthe corners of the buildings use the\nsidewalk necessarily, it is true, but\nit would seem to be the duty of the\ndriver to give some warning before\nhe starts, or at leant in time to pre\nvent accidents.\nBIRTH OF SON\nTO RANCH FAMILY\nDr. Markley reports the birth of a\non to Mr. and Mrs. Will Hunziker ol\nthe Oda Mason ranch, mother am\n\u25a0abe bring at the 1 vinson hospital, and\nloing nicely. The daughter of Dr\n\u2019\u2022'aukrnntein of West Ixiramle was op\nrated on at tho 1 vlnson hospital by\nDr. Markley, and is also doing well\n'J. W. ADMITTED\nTO CONFERENCE\nThe University of Wyoming was ad\nmitted to full membership in th<\nRocky Mountain conference at tht\nAocky- Mountain Faculty Athletic con\nference held Saturday in Denver. Thb\nmeans that Wyoming is now on a pat\nwith the other teams of the confer\n*nce and will receive duo credit foi\ndetoriea won. On the other band i\nneans that she is subject to the strict\nir rules of the conference, which wll\nhandicap her for a year or so, bu\nwhich, in the cud, will bo best boti\nor the teams and for the institu\ntlun. as standards in both are sure t<\n>e raised by the observance.\nWyoming wns also placed on tht\nist of those Uistltuticas eligible t<\nhold conference office. This meant\nthat in a few years, by rotatJon, th>\nWyoming faculty representative auto\nnatkally assumes the duties of presi\nlent of the conference.\nThe conference admitted to artilia\n:ion the state normal school at Gunn\nson. Colorado, and made several im\n\u2019ortant changes in the eligibility rules\nlr\u00dft of the latter obliges freshmet\nto have a full year\u2019s rosidon^c befon\nHaying on varsity teams. This rule\nbowe\\ er, does not go into effect un\nil next January, so Wyoming, present\nresUraen are eligible for this seasons\n>asketball. In addition, freshmen an\nof ineiigiHcs, raised the pay of football\nvith a similar class of any conference\ninstitutkw.\nThe conference tightened up on tht\nmigrant-.and proteas^onsl rules, volet\ndown all ^petitions fer reinstatemem\nIneligtbles, raised the pay of foutbai\nofficials, and decided to hold the next\ntnnual meeting the second Ualurda:\nafter Thanksgiving day.\nAthletic gshedules.\nThe members of the conference rat\nifitMl the athletic schedules, d awn ui\nhe previous evenfug by the coaches\nWyoming plays every Colorado insti\n\u2019utlun m foothail <with the exception ol\nthe state- university. It was found im\npossible to find a date which both in\n\u00abtltuti<>ns had open for such a game\nin addition the normal college a\nGunnisbn is taken on-for a game ir\nLaramic, in early* November, and i\nrip will be taken-to Utah where both\nhe university and the state coileg*\nwill be played. Final basketball an;\nbaseball nchedules were arranged a:\nallows.\nBasketball.\nJan. H. Colorado College st Larnmle\nJan. 21. Denver university at Den\nver.\nJan 22. Colorado College at Colors\nlo Springs.\nFt b. Denver university at Lara\n\u2022nle.\nFob. 11 and 12. Colorado Agricultur\nil olleKe at Fort Collins.\nThe Fort Collins games cull for two\n;ume\u00ab here In 1922.\nBaseball.\nApril 21, Mines.at Golden.\nApril 22 nnd 23, Colorado college al\nColorado Springs.\nMay 18, University of Colorado at\nBoulder.\nMay 19, Denver university at Den\nver.\nMay 20, Colorado Agricultural col\nlege at Fort Collins.\nJune 8, Colorado Schol of Mines nt\nLaramie.\nThe date of the conference track\nmeet is June 21, and Boulder has the\nhonor of entertaining the other confer\nence schools.\nHELD SERVICES AT\nOHIO OIL CAMP\nCaptain A. O. Winters of the Salva\ntion Army was at the Ohio oil camp\nlast week, holding services in the hall\nthere, and today slated that he was\nvery. agreeably surprised and greatly\npleased at the reception tendered bfm,\nbelieving that he ited done some good\nfor the cause. Oaptafn Winters says\nOhio City is ope of the most modem\ncities of its site (p ttuMmuntry, with\nmany nwderg gonytnMbees, some that\neven the InHHt elUee lteve not. Na\ntural gas is naed..for nominating and\nMating, and many the kttchone Are\nsupplied with It tdr Hie ranges. Elec\ntric lights help ott the illumination,\nand there are many other things that\ndwellers in mors modern cities are\ndented. Ho tetends to go again,\nCONFESSES\nHOU\nA man named Connery has been\narrested here, charged with being the\nringleader In the robbery of the Mecca\nHillard Parlor a few nights ago. and\nhas taken unto himself the whole j\nblame for the robbery, although T.,\nfl. Murphy was arrested in Cheyenne,\nto be brought back here, and L. J\nDwyer was placed in the county Jail\nThe greater part of the loot obtained;\nin the haul has been recovered, much\nof it being found in Connery's room.\nThis included a $5 gold piece, a $2 5b\ngold piece and a 50-cent gold piece\nthe latter being very *are, made by\nCalifornia in the gold rush days. The\nman claims to have used a hacksaw\nin sawing the hasp from the rear\ndoor, and that he was alone in the\nmatter, but the police had enough\n\u2018on\" Murphy and Dwyer to justify j\ntheir* arrest. The burglar, once inside\nthe building, made a search lor\nmoney, and finding none of current\nfunds, helped himself to the jewelry\nround in the drawer, with the gold\n\u2022olns. Janies Harry, the owner of the\n.ewelry and the coins, advertised in\nThe Republican Saturday afternoon,\nhe advertisement reading: \u201cStolen\u2014\nProm the Mecca Biliiatfl Parlor, wed\nling ring and other articles of Jewel\n\u2022y valued as keepsakes. Liberal re\nward and no questions asked if re\nturned to James Barry at the Mecca.\u201d\nCaught 0y Restaurateur.\nThe burglar ale at the Brann res\naurant on Saturday, and gave one oi\nhe gold pieces in payment for the\nood he ate, and also selling the 50-\n:ent gold piece to a man in Mr.\ntrann\u2019s place of business.\nMr. Brann when he read the ac\nount of the robbery and the ad in\nThe Republican, concerning the loss\nif the wedding ring recalled the Inci\nlent of the man giving a 12.50 gold\npiece for his meal earlier iu tho day.\nHe went to the Mecca and informed,\ndr. Barry and on returning to hit\ndace of business maw the man. JR\n'ailed Policeman Cameron who placed\nhe man, Connory, under arrest.\nAll the articles have been recovered.\nThese Included Mr. Barry\u2019s mother's\nwedding ring, whch she wore for\nnany years and which tho son was\n-.eeping for her sake. An* Elk charm,\nwith two sets of elk teeth, was not\nhard to Identify, and a child\u2019s ring\nvas also among the goods taken\nWarrants are being filed charging the\niian with burglarizing the store.\nWord camo to the sheriff's office 1\n\u2022n Sundar that T. Murphy had\njeen arrested' that day, and a deputy\nsheriff went to Cheyenne to bring\nilm to Laramie. Connery says that\nvehhcr Murphy nor Dwyer had a hand\nn the robbery, and that he alone\nlulled the stunt. The outcome of this\neature of the case is being watched\nwith interest. The 50-cent piece waif\nme of the main articles used to iden\nity the goods found, although Mr\n4aVrj had no difficulty with the\nwatch, the Elk charm and the child\u2019s\nIng. to say nothing of the wedding\nring, into which a small guard rim\nhad worn itself, making a very pc\nruliar combination It in almost c.er\nsin that the man will Ime sent to lilt\nstate prison.\nThe three-day session of the Stat*\n\u2018\u2022\u2019arm Bureau conference was brought\no a successful close on Saturday aft\nw>on, tho newly elected officers hav\nng been published In The Republics!\nif that Issue. Today tho mootings o'\nthe extension workers wore begun\nthe address by A. B. Graham. special\nIst from Washington, being one of the\nmoat. Important features. The rest of\n\u2022he morning meeting was devoted t.\nreports from various counties.\nThis afternoon sectional conference\nwere held, the county agents. (h\u00bb\n'ionic demonstration agent a and th\nToys and girls' culb workers moetlnj\nn different groups to discuss th** prob\nems of their vaMous lines of work.\nDirector and Mrs. A. E Bowman\nire entertaining this evening at thei\nionic for all the extension workers.\nThe new electric-driven conveyors\nat the re-icing station of the Pacihc\nFruit Express are being given a try\nout twenty-live curs of ice from the\nUnion Pacific ponds having been sent\nto tho station for unloading The\nconveyors are driven by a ninety\nhorsepower motor, with curt ent from\nthe city plant, and so far the convey\nor\u00ae have worked too rapidly, the trie\ntoday being to determine if the tre\nmendous load of Ice on the belts Will\nslow the motor down to the requtreo\nspeed. Mbre than 1,200 cars of >cf\nare to be stored there, making the icr\nharvest in Laramie the largest ever\nundertaken. The cutting and loading\nstations are the meat modern In the\nwest, and will compare favorably In\ndevices used with the great ide plants\nof New York state.\nHERB FOR A VISIT\nWITH HIS BROTHER\nJudge John R. Arnold of Evanston,\njudge of the Third judicial district,\nwas in the citv today, the guest of the\nfamilies of his brother, C. P. Arnold,\nand his nephew, T. W. Arnold. He\nhad some business In the court at\nRawlins, and came to thio city, stop\nping off here on h\u2018s way to Cheyenne.\nHe Went to that city later In the day.\naccompanied by his nephew, Thurman\nArnold understaking his legislative du-\nIMS tomorrow, with the convening of\ntho lower nonee.\nI JURY COMMISSION\nWILL MEET TUESDAY\nThe jury commission of Albany\ncounty, consisting of Chairman Woolf\nof the board of county commissiners.\nCounty Clerk Beltz and County Treas\nurer Featherstone, will meet Tuesday\nto make up tho Jury list for tho county,\nusing the county assessment rolls lor\nthe purpose. The list will be fur\nnished to Clerk Ihmsen of the district\ncourt, who will use the names for fill\ning the Jury boxes, from which the\nseveral panels are drawn from time\nto lime. About 2.000 names of men\nliable to Jury service are written in\nthe list.\nuA*\nTHE DAY'S BUSINESS\nOVER THE DISTRICT\nThcrq were 18 eastbound freight 1\ntrains Friday, with 470 loaded and\n272 empty curs. The average load\nwas 1.855 tons and the average time I\n7 hours. 21 minutes. Westward there,\nwere 19 trains, with an average time I\nof 5 hours, minute, an average ton- 1\nnage of 572 in 214 loaded and 231 i\nempty cars. One to four inches of\nold snow lay on the ground and night 1\ntemperatures were from 10 to 12 inch-j\nes above. The temperature ranged in\nYaramie was from 30 degrees above,\nto 10 degrees above.\nMUCH INTEREST TAKEN\nIN THECONEERENCE\nOFFARMBUREAUHERE\nThe Extension conference sessions\nwere continued today, with Interest\ning programs at both the morning and\nafternoon meetings, and all tho taikr\nare proving not only very entertain\ning but of much profit to ail those in\n(created in the work.\n8. L.Striving, who is president 01\nthe N\u00abw York'Farm Bureau, with its\nenormous membership, la proving-one\nof the most Interesting speakers. Hie\naddress opened the morning meeting.\nOther talks were given by A. H. Bow\nman, president of the Crook County\nbureau, A. F. Burton- of the Lin\ncoln county bureau and U. G. Johns\nof the executive committee of the state\nbureau, while several of the county\nagents and farm bureau delegates took\npart in a discussion of various prob\nIsms of the bureau. This afternoon\nsectional conferences were held.\nToday\u2019s session conclude thode fm\nthe farm bureau, and beginning Mon\nday there will be throe days\u2019 work tor\nthe extension faculty, with addresses\nby- tho speclalils and discussions ol\n1 all kinds.\nNEWS NOTES FROM\nROCK SPRINGS MINER\n>Tss Bertha While has returned to\nher school In Ijnamie, after spending\n\u2022he holidays at her home In this dty.\nMiss Meredith l^ngholdl teacher ai\nthe North Side school, who spent the\nholidays in Cheyenne and Laramie\nreturned Monday morning.\nMr. and Mrs. Ben Whlsonand ar\nrived this week from Ixiramie ai\u00abi\nwill take charge of the'Rc.^k Springs\nPharmacy while Mr. and Mrs. J. R,\nWhisenand make a visit to California,\nwhere they may decide to locale per\nmanently.\nMisses Isabel VanDcusen, Evelyn\nEllas, Edna Johnson. Bessie Sparks.\nMary I\u2019ark, Date! Hilling, MUrjorlo\n\u2019heddon. XTiry Hay. Donna Bronka\nClara Hickerson and Tom Farinelli\nand James fTyde have returned to\nluiramie where thev aro students at\nUie University, af\u00bber spending the\nholidays In Rock Springs.\nCOMMITTEE TO MEET\nAT THE CITY HALL\nAgent A. B. Cady of Um 1-aramte\nreigbt office has called a meeting ol\nhe jiixth district committee on cause\u2019\n4nd prevention of accidents, to be held\nit tht offices of the Council of Indus\nry. at the City hall, on Wednesday,\nJanuary 12. at 10 a. tn. The commu\nte consists of the agents, trainmas\nters. some conductors and other rail\nroad men on the sixth district, from\nl^ramio to Rawlins, and its meetings\nire held monthly.\nTENTATIVE SCHEDULES\nFOR FOOTBALL GAMES\nThe following tentative schedules\nfor football games next season, the.\nprobability being that Wyoming will\nlie admitted to the conference, were\narranged at tho meeting of the sched\nule committee at Denver:\nOctober I\u2014-Wyoming at Fort Collins.\nOctober B\u2014Colorado College at\nI ji ramie.\nOctober li-4Utdh Aggies at Logan.\nOctober 15 \u2014Utah at Salt take.\nOctober 23\u2014Mines at l*aramia.\nOctober 29\u2014Wyoming at Denver.\nARRANGING DETAIL\nFOR EAR MEETING\nClyde M. Watts, who heads the com\nmittee making arrangements for the\nannual meeting of th* Wyoming\nState Bar association In Cheyenne\nnext week, announced Saturday that\n\u2666hp sessions would be held in the\nstate supreme court room at the cap\u00bb-\ntol, and that a banquet would be held\nThursday evening kt the Plains, says\nthe Cheyenne Tribune. The meet\nings are 1g begin Thursday morning\nand last through Friday. r\nFOREIGN AUTOMODES\nAT YELLOWSTONE PARK\nSlxty-onc automobile* from Can\nada, Mexico and Hawaii were regis\ntered when entering the Yollewstose\nNational park last seasun.\nPAGE SEVEN\nTOOK LOOK\nONGROUND\nDEMOCRATIC MINORITY IN LOW\nER HOUSE SEES TO THINGS\nFROM HIS VIEW.POINT\nBy J. C. Thompson.\nSoeclftl to the Laramie Republican.\nCheyenne, Wyo., Jan 7.\u2014Thurman\nW. Arnold of Laramie, Albany coun\nty representative-elect in the Six\nteenth legislature, was in Cheyenne\nThursday, looking over the grou'nd of\nprospective activities. Mr. Arnold waa\nview.ng the field of operations with\ntho eye of a general, keen for strate\ngic advantages. A heavy legislative\nresponsibility rests upon him, a res\nponsibility heavier than that or any\nother representative\u2014he Is tho dOmo\ncratic minority of the lower house,\n\u2019Sfacl\u2014Mr Ainold is, among the six\nty-!lve members of the legislature\nelected last November, tho only dem\nocrat. The distinction of being the\nonly democratic member of the Six\nteenth legislature would have bcca\nIlls had It not been that members or\nthe senate are elected for four-year\nterms \u2014a portion of tho membership\nat one election and the balance at tho\nsucceeding election. Bvcauso of this\narrangement there are three ddtno\ncrats in the senate who were elected In\n1918, Senator F- P (Tanney of Lin\ncto\u2019.n, Senator Pcta 1 J. Shinazy ot\nSweetwater county and Senator W\nS. Green of Washakie county. Elec\ntion results in Lincoln, Sweotwaier\nand Washakie counties in 1920 wng\ngest that had there been senatorial\nelections In those counties last No\nvember the membership of the sen\nate of the Sixteenth legislature would\nhave been solidly republican, and Mr.\nArnold would have been the total\nlemocratic minority of tho now leg\nislature.\nAn Interesting story regarding Mr.\nArnold's election-said to explain his\nsuccess when every-other dehiocralic\nlegislative candidate wws over\nwhelmed by the republican landslide\nhai swept Wyoming last Novtmber--\nis related. He is a courteous, aRe bis.\nhighly popular young attorney\u2014n na\ntive son of luiramie and scion of one\nof the ablest and most distinguished\nmembers of the Wyoming bar\u2014Hut\nthese facts; it is related, \u2018Wimid met\nhave been sufficient to have pulled\nhlnr successfully through the election.\nThere was another pregwant WdftW\nwhich contributed vitally to Jain suo\ncess\u2014the fact that one of the repub\nlican candidates in Albany county for\nthe lower house had \u201cposted\" his es\ntate against anglers, forbidding\ntresiiass upon his ground by persona\ndesiring to enjoy the excellent trout\nfishing to be found tn tire waters there\nin The result. It is related, Is that\nvirtually every confirmed angler of the\nregion, regardless of race, pol.ttcs or\ncreed, toted against this candidate,\nand Arnold, most popular representa\ntive of discredited democracy, was\nelected.\nDANISH BROTHERHOOD\nELECTS ITS OFFICERS\nThe Danish Brotherhood held-\nspecial meeting last evening -at Mobae\nhall for the purpose of electing offi\ncers. this business having been post\nposed because of the failure'to hoW\na session just before Christmas. Tho\nfollowing elections wore made:\nPast President -Thomas Haugaard.\nPresident \u2014Carl Olson.\nVice president\u2014Jens Pedersen.\n(\u2018orrespond ing Secretary\u2014-Chris\nChristensen.\nFinancial Secretary\u2014James A. Mil\nler.\nTreasurer \u2014Mike Michelsen^\nTrustee, three year term\u2014 -Chris\nMadsen.\nGuide\u2014Chris Andersen.\nInner Guard\u2014 James K. Johnson.\nOuter Guard\u2014 Hana Thlasenlga.\nThe Danish Sisterhood has invited\n^he Brotherhood (or a Joint IhstaUa-*\nt*on on Friday evening, January 14, to\nbe held at Moose hall. Mijmbera ot\nthe Arotherhood and their families ara\nInvited to be present.\nDEAN OF COLLEGE\nAUTHOR OF TEXTBOOR\nDean C. R. Maxwell, of the college\nof education at the Cniveritty of Wyo\nming. received notification yesterday\nthat his book, \u201cThe Selection of\nBooks,\" which is being published tit'\nthe Houghton. Mifflin company\ngone to press, and that he woMdtatyti\nbe in receipt of